arate discovery issues, I’m thinking about renaming DirectJUnit4Case to something that doesn’t end in \\\"Test.\\\" Since the JUnit4 class name isn’t crucial for the runner, I wonder if Gradle can discover all classes based on their file patterns. The JUnit engine scans the classpath, and I might be safer by renaming nested helper classes as well. However, existing nested classes like GetNameOnlyTest might still be acceptable. It seems like I could rename helpers to something like SuiteMethodFixture or DirectJUnit4Fixture to avoid direct test discovery. But I also need to consider how Gradle scans classes with @Test annotations, regardless of names.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering JUnit discovery patterns**\\n\\nI'm thinking about how JUnit scans compiled classes and implements platform discovery. It seems like it might include patterns like *Tests? The test configuration might set this up. I'm curious about how specific these patterns need to be. Do they rely on naming conventions? I want to ensure I'm considering all possible implications for how tests are recognized within the framework. Understanding this could help clarify how to organize my tests effectively.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_T1CoenlYb3i1piMVKbMJAiDx|fc_092ad9018afe4883016a263b7ed6c0819091241e01e9e5b480", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "git diff -- tests/src/org.apache.ant/ant-junit/1.10.15/src/test/java/org_apache_ant/ant_junit/JUnitTestRunnerTest.java"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 352, "output": 803, "cacheRead": 28160, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 29315, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1780890476764, "responseId": "resp_092ad9018afe4883016a263b6d44808190ad67c6d9f87b2a8d"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_T1CoenlYb3i1piMVKbMJAiDx|fc_092ad9018afe4883016a263b7ed6c0819091241e01