[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Analyzing JUnit integration**\n\nIt seems that ant-junit doesn’t include CustomJUnit4TestAdapterCache, which may mean the JUnit4 path isn’t accessible. I’m thinking about how to navigate JUnit3 instead, using a TestCase subclass to scan methods. The getDeclaredClasses recursion needs to consider inner classes, right? I’ll use JUnit3TestFixture that extends TestCase with a public test method. If I enable skipNonTests, it’ll scan declared inner classes first, even non-TestCase inner classes. I'll design a static JUnit3ScanFixture class to manage this.\n\n**Renaming suite methods**\n\nI’m considering renaming SuiteMethodTest to SuiteMethodFixture and SuiteMethodTestCase to SuiteMethodCase. If the name ends with \"TestCase,\" it might be discovered as a test class, which could complicate things since Gradle patterns usually include *Test, *Tests, or *TestCase. I’m thinking about failure scenarios for SuiteMethodTest but maybe renaming to MethodSuiteCase could help. I also need to ensure that JUnit3 TestCase subclasses are public and consider the implications for nested classes and discovery patterns. It might be necessary to edit the file accordingly.\n\n**Clarifying JUnit3ScanFixture construction**\n\nI’m thinking about the JUnit3ScanFixture class that extends TestCase. I’m considering whether it needs an explicit public no-argument constructor. If the class is public, the default constructor should be public too, right? So if it’s a public static nested class, it definitely has a public no-arg constructor generated by the compiler. This should ensure it can work correctly within the JUnit framework during test execution. I just want to be clear on the construction rules for JUnit.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_092ad9018afe4883016a263b9c535881908e031743c24e6c20\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqJjunRvYbE-X3ftTypTZQ8HR